To see the data within a table in MariaDB using the command line, you can use the SELECT statement. Here's the basic syntax:

sql

SELECT * FROM your_table_name;

Replace your_table_name with the actual name of the table you want to query. If you want to see specific columns, you can replace * with the column names separated by commas.

Here's an example:

sql

SELECT column1, column2 FROM your_table_name;

To see all data in all columns of a table, use the asterisk *:

sql

SELECT * FROM your_table_name;

Here's a step-by-step guide:

    Open a terminal window.

    Access the MariaDB command-line interface:

    bash

mysql -u your_username -p

After entering your password, switch to the database containing the table:

sql

USE your_database_name;

View the data in the table:

sql

    SELECT * FROM your_table_name;


